<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-676-385  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 676 385.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Nov 1 1990 v29 n21 p74(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software architecture mates user applications with DSPfunctionality. (Spectron Microsystems' Spox signal-processingoperating system) (digital signal processing) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Williams, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Spectron Microsystems introduces the Spox signal-processingoperating system providing application portability among variousdigital signal processing (DSP) hardware, including chips fromTexas Instruments, Motorola and Analog Devices.andP;  Spectron's OpenSignal Processing Architecture (OSPA) lets applications runningunder operating systems resident on the host CPU, such asMicrosoft Windows/DOS and X Windows/Unix, and that run separatefrom the DSP hardware access DSP programs as if they were anoperating system resource.andP;  Spox forms the core of OSPA; thereal-time multitasking operating system is designed specificallyto provide run-time support for compute- and I/O-intensive DSPfunctions.andP;  Spox includes the Spox-LINK communications component,the Spox-RTK real-time kernel and the Spox-DSP set of general DSPfunctions; all three are packaged as libraries of C-callablefunctions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Spectron Microsystems (Product introduction).andO;Product:   SPOX (Operating system) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Real-Time SystemsOperating SystemsProduct IntroductionDigital Signal ProcessingMultitasking.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The Open Signal Processing Architecture. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>